Attendance Time and Intercolony Movements

Author

Eleanor

Here are three potential approaches for calculating attendance time and inter-colony movements. My goal is to use the same dataframe for both of those statistics. I want to 1) include times when birds are in burrows or crevices in attendance time, 2) judiciously include birds that are only being detected on one antenna per receiver, 3) exclude birds that are in between or transiting between Gull and Great Island where possible, and 4) minimize the rapid, vacillating âmovementsâ between Great and Gull Island that likely reflect VHF noisiness instead of inter-colony movements.

One minute bins, antenna then power priority, one-minute IC movements removed.

This is the most similar to approaches youâve seen before. Detections are grouped into one-minute bins (one minute = one scan cycle). Each bin is then assigned to an island. The assignment is done first based on the number of antennas pinged (e.g., if a bird pings two Great Island antennas and one Gull Island antenna, it is on Great Island). If the number of antennas pinged is equal (most commonly one antenna each from Great and Gull), then assignment is done based on which receiver recorded the higher average transmission power in that scan cycle. This approach is the most inclusive of one-antenna runs of detections, which means it is also the most inclusive of those short, one-cycle vacillations that look like impossibly brief inter-colony movements.

We exclude three individual bird-minutes (each belonging to a different bird) where both the total power received and the number of antennas represented was equal for Great and Gull Island.

visitors <- prospecting_detections %>%
  filter(nightdate != capture_nightdate) %>%
  group_by(tag_id) %>%
  count() %>%
  dplyr::select(tag_id)

visitors <- as.list(visitors$tag_id) ## Gives a list of every bird that returned at least once

assigned_to_islands <- prospecting_detections %>% 
  mutate(bin = binner(datetime, "1 mins")) %>% 
  mutate(direction = case_when(bearing == 196 ~ "Gull-south",
                                 bearing == 16 ~ "Gull-north",
                                 bearing == 106 ~ "Gull-east",
                                 bearing == 286 ~ "Gull-west",
                                 bearing == 325 ~ "Great-northwest",
                                 bearing == 235 ~ "Great-southwest",
                                 bearing == 145 ~ "Great-southeast",
                                 bearing == 55 ~ "Great-northeast",
                                 bearing == 343 ~ "Baccalieu-north",
                                 bearing == 73 ~ "Baccalieu-east",
                                 bearing == 163 ~ "Baccalieu-south",
                                 bearing == 253 ~ "Baccalieu-west",
                                 .default = "NA")) %>% 
  group_by(tag_id, bin, direction) %>% 
  summarize(mean_power = mean(power)) %>% 
  mutate(island = case_when(direction %in% c("Gull-south", "Gull-north", "Gull-east", "Gull-west") ~ "Gull",
                            direction %in% c("Great-northwest", "Great-southeast", "Great-southwest", "Great-northeast") ~ "Great",
                            direction %in% c("Baccalieu-north", "Baccalieu-south", "Baccalieu-south", "Baccalieu-north") ~ "Baccalieu")) %>% 
  group_by(tag_id, bin, island) %>% 
  summarize(n_antennas = length(unique(direction)), mean_power = mean(mean_power)) %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = "island", values_from = c("n_antennas", "mean_power"), values_fill = 0) %>% 
  select(-mean_power_NA, -n_antennas_NA) %>% 
  rename(gull_antennas = n_antennas_Gull, 
         great_antennas = n_antennas_Great, 
         gull_power = mean_power_Gull, 
         great_power = mean_power_Great,
         bac_antennas = n_antennas_Baccalieu, 
         bac_power = mean_power_Baccalieu) %>% 
  mutate(area = if_else(bac_antennas > 0, "Baccalieu", "Witless Bay")) %>% 
  mutate(island = case_when(area == "Witless Bay" & gull_antennas > great_antennas ~ "Gull",
                            area == "Witless Bay" & great_antennas > gull_antennas ~ "Great",
                            area == "Witless Bay" & gull_antennas == great_antennas ~ "Both",
                            area == "Baccalieu" ~ "Baccalieu")) %>% 
  mutate(island = case_when(island == "Both" & gull_power > great_power ~ "Gull",
                            island == "Both" & gull_power < great_power ~ "Great",
                            island != "Both" ~ island,
                            .default = NA)) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(island))

The next step uses two nested for loops to group our bird-minutes into segments. The first loop simply iterates by tag ID so that we consider each bird separately. The second loop loops through each island-assigned bird-minute that we created above (dataset arranged chronologically) and assigns it a segment number. The segment number starts at 1 and increases by 1 when either 1) the assigned island changes, or 2) the ânight-ofâ date changes. Therefore each segment ends when the bird either 1) changes island or 2) leaves the area for the night. This should address periods where the bird is in a burrow or crevice, as long as it is detected at least once on the island in question after leaving the burrow or crevice. Each segment can be considered an individual colony âvisitâ. We can then calculate the length of each segment by subtracting the time of the first bird-minute in each segment (its arrival on that island for that visit) from the last bird-minute in each segment (its last minute present before departure). In this case I am only considering birds which came back to visit the island at least once after being tagged, but it would be simple to include the others (I have excluded them only because it seems likely that their colony attendance behaviour on the night of tagging would be affected by being captured, and the night of capture represents our only data for those birds).

visit_segments_loop <- data.frame() #For the record, this is the line of code that the last version was missing, which means that each time I ran the for loop, I was adding on to the existing dataset of segments instead of making a new, blank dataframe. It made all the colony attendance numbers look super inflated. 


for (i in visitors) { #Create iterating segment numbers

groups = list(1)
counter = 1

df <- assigned_to_islands %>% 
  filter(tag_id == i) %>% 
  mutate(nightdate = nightdater(bin))

  for (n in 2:length(df$tag_id)) {
  
    if (df$island[n] == df$island[n-1] & as.character(df$nightdate[n]) == as.character(df$nightdate[n-1])) {
      groups <- append(groups,counter)
     # print("same")
     } else {
      counter = counter + 1
      groups <- append(groups,counter)

      #print("dif")
    }
  
  }

groups <- as.data.frame(groups) 

groups <- groups %>% 
  pivot_longer(everything())

df <- cbind(df, groups$value) %>% 
  dplyr::rename(segment = `...12`)

visit_segments_loop <- rbind(visit_segments_loop, df)
}

Approach Two: Only include bins where at least two antennas (on one receiver) are pinged

In this case we will still group detections into one-minute bins, but then we will remove any bins where fewer than two antennas (from at least one island) are pinged in that minute. In this case the segmenter loop will include periods where the bird is detected on only one antenna in attendance time, as long as it is detected by at least two antennas on that island at least once before leaving, which is certainly not a given. The same antenna then power priority rules for assignment apply. This should reduce the number of inter-colony movements and the attendance time by removing periods where the bird is between islands and only appearing on one antenna per receiver. I am afraid that this will remove real attendance time, for example, if a bird is sitting on Baccalieu only in range of the north-facing antenna.

As expected, we end up with fewer segments, but still many that are only one minute in length. In this case I donât think we need to filter those out, because those are still minutes when at least two antennas detect a bird, so they might just be short fly-overs. But weâll see how they affect our inter-colony movement count.

We now end up with:

We can try another approach with a more complicated island assignment critera to try and get the best of both worlds.

Approach Three: Island assignment based on two antennas OR frequent appearance on one antenna

You suggested using a criteria that looks at the percentage of possible detections occuring on a single antenna. Because each antenna is scanned for 15 seconds per scan cycle, a bird that is close to the receiver will be detected twice by each antenna in each cycle. One option is to assign birds to the island where one antenna is being pinged IF they ping that antenna, on average, more than once per scan cycle.

In this case, it doesnât make sense to use one minute bins, because we need more data to determine if a bird is pinging an antenna regularly. However, using larger bins will slightly inflate our attendance time, because it will round all of our segments up to at least the length of that bin. Letâs try with three-minute bins and see if our attendance time looks too inflated.

In this case, I will consider a bird to be on an island if it pings at least two antennas (on that island) OR if it pings one antenna at least four times in three minutes. Antenna number will still be the first priority for breaking ties. But in the case of one-antenna ties, I will here use the number of pings in the three-minute interval as a tiebreaker (and then power if I have to).

This leaves us with 2,570 three-minute bins where a bird was defined as âpresentâ on an island (our strict two-antenna criteria gave us 2252 one-minute bins, so we are reclaiming some time). We loop through the bins normally to split them into segments.

We end up with a lot of three-minute (our new minimum) segments. We may need to filter these out.

I feel like this solution is on the right track in terms of incorporating periods where birds are on one antenna per island. But Iâm not super happy with these criteria. Maybe longer bins or requiring more detections per bin would help. But of course, there is never going to be a clear distinction between birds in one-antenna areas and birds making inter-colony movements. There is just a fundamental ambiguity in which Witless Bay Island a bird is on at a time.

My inclination would be to go with either the first approach here (with one-minute segments filtered out) or the third.

We could also simply use a different criteria for Baccalieu, since thereâs no issue of overlap, and allow any number of detections to count, there.

How well does method 2 do with our georeferenced points?

We have a dataframe of GPS-referenced VHF detections; we can use the same assignment criteria to see where those points get assigned. We donât need to run the segmenter for loops, we can just assign them to islands and then map them.

I will group them into three-minute bins; in order to get one position per bin, Iâll just average the lat and lon from all points in that bin. This is probably not kosher.

I didnât send these points through the segmenter loop, but presumably many of these unassigned points would be included in segments.

Our problem areas are exactly where weâd expect. All in all I think this works pretty well and using the two-step criteria is probably acceptable.

What if we just drop our two problem antennas?

In this case, I will assign birds based on our first critera (antenna then power priority and one-minute bins, but only one antenna required) and just remove the northeast-facing antenna on Great Island and the south-facing antenna on Gull Island from the dataset entirely.

In the case of one-minute bins, adding a qualifier that would use the âback-shadowâ of those antennasâ opposite antenna doesnât make senseâdetections on the back-shadow antennas will cause the minute in which they occur to be included in the attendance time anyway. This is also as generous as possible with the Baccalieu detections.

We end up with 4,788 bird-minutes of colony attendance. Without filtering those two antennas, we would have 8,230. So we are losing quite a bit of attendance time, but weâll see how much of that time gets picked back up by the segmenter loop.

So we lose a single case where a bird (it was #203) was only ever detected on Great Islandâs problem antenna, and dropping that antenna drops Great Island altogether from its list of islands visited. That Great Island hit was on the night it was tagged, anyway, and very brief, so I think this is a totally fair loss (plus the bird was obviously never actually on Great Island, because it was only in the area at all for a couple of minutes after being tagged).

Iâm a little grumpy about how well this works, because I hate to drop so much data, but it suggests that what we know about the antenna ranges is accurate. Removing our problem antennas gives us almost exactly the same mean colony attendance time per bird as our most generous approach (one minute bins without the shortest segments filtered out), removes the need to filter the shortest segments, and cleans up our inter-colony movements to what I think is a reasonable count. We also wonât have to explain a multi-step criteria in the methods and this method is as generous as possible to Baccalieu. I am surprised by how little dropping those antennas affects colony attendance, but I guess birds frequently ping multiple antennas as they arrive or leave, since they probably cross open areas, and arrival/departure is all that really matters for the segmenter loop.
